// buildInfo.js — the phase/version label and changelog shown in the Settings
// drawer's "Build" panel. Hand-maintained: bump PHASE/VERSION and prepend a
// note each time a phase ships, so a returning GM can see at a glance what
// changed without digging through git history.

export const BUILD = {
  phase: '10',
  version: '0.10.5',
  label: 'Phase 10: Merchant Rules Lens, Faction Pressure Track, Missions, Faction Turns, Traveller/SWN/CWN Content',
  notes: [
    '2026-07-06 next-request.md batch: Cybernetics renamed to "Enhancements" (domain/enhancements.js, tolerant legacy read of old `cyberware` data) with a per-item type dropdown (Cybernetics/Wetware-Bio-Genetics/Psionics/Gene-Modification, always shown), collapsed by default, moved under the statblock section, and its 🎲 roll now lands in the add-form\'s name field (overwritten by each reroll, not journaled) instead of a toast+Journal entry, until "Install" commits it. deepenNpc\'s Want/Complication now append to Revealed/hidden (GM) instead of Overview; Revealed/hidden is collapsed by default and persistently stays expanded (entity.revealedOpen) once a GM opens it. Changing an entity\'s Type now confirms via window.confirm before applying. Cast search matches entity type too. Fixed: Oracle search couldn\'t find "Creature Concept" (a composite-generator label, not a literal table name) — GROUP_ALIASES in data/oracleGroups.js. Trade Economy Types (docs/adr/0013): a Location tag can now name an economy type (data/economyTypes.js — Hostile-native or "(Traveller-style)" models, one active at a time via settings.tradeEconomyModel) biasing domain/trade.js\'s priceAt() via scarcity/manufacturing dials instead of a literal tech level; switching models never breaks an already-tagged Location. Game Mechanics Index (docs/adr/0014): a real PDF.js-backed scan (vendored assets/vendor/pdfjs/, one explicit exception to the zero-dependency policy) links game-mechanic terms to their page in the Reference Library from a new Settings "🔄 Refresh Mechanics Index" button, surfaced as clickable links in the Guide drawer — found and handled a real file:// limitation (Chromium blocks reading a local PDF\'s bytes over file://; this one feature needs `npm run serve`) and fixed a real scripts/build.js bundler gap (`export async function` wasn\'t recognized).',
    '2026-07-06 SWN content deepened, CWN cybernetics borrowed, on direct user request after the real Stars Without Number Revised Deluxe and Cities Without Number Deluxe PDFs were added to assets/docs/ (docs/adr/0011-swn-cwn-content.md, extending docs/adr/0010 rather than replacing it — still original content/phrasing throughout, not a transcription of either book\'s actual text/tables). Faction creation: force/cunning/wealth stats (0-10, entities.js) plus a growing Assets list, with a "Faction Asset" oracle table (Corporate Powers group) to roll-and-append one. Turn-based mini-game: domain/factions.js\'s resolveFactionTurn() resolves a faction\'s turn as d10 + its acting stat (Attack/force, Scheme/cunning, Expand/wealth, weighted toward whichever stat is already strongest) vs. a flat difficulty — a strong success raises that stat, a setback adds an extra Pressure Track tick — wired into both the existing bulk "Advance Faction Turns" action and a new per-faction "▶ Turn" button on the Faction card. Deepening NPCs: domain/session.js\'s deepenNpc() rolls new Stereotype/Want/Complication oracle tables onto an EXISTING NPC\'s Overview via a "🎲 Deepen" button in Entity Detail, distinct from generateNpc\'s from-scratch chain. Styling creatures/places/adventure seeds: domain/worldbuilding.js adds three small combinatorial generators — Creature Concept (a new Xenobestiary oracle group: Origin/Method/Trait/Threat), Site Concept (Feature/Danger/Wonder), and Adventure Seed (Hook/Twist, reusing the existing Story Complication table for its third beat) — each with its own Journal drawer roll button. CWN\'s best-known subsystem, cyberware costing Strain against a limited capacity, landed as a new domain/cybernetics.js module (installCyberware/removeCyberware/isOverStrained) and a Cybernetics section in the NPC inspector, with an "Augmentation" oracle group for flavor ideas — deliberately not a new RULES_PROVIDERS entry, since CWN was never one of the six systems the original Rules Constitution roster named.',
    '2026-07-06 Design roadmap reconciliation, round two: ADR 0008 (the gameplay-mechanics.md reconciliation) explicitly declined five proposals; each was put back to the user individually afterward, non-binding and suggestive, rather than treated as a final call. Documentation only, no code yet: `docs/adr/0009-situation-engine-revisited.md` records the result — Expedition Structure and Diplomacy Engine\'s per-faction fields were reversed (scoped: a new `domain/expeditions.js` giving a `kind: \'expedition\'` Thread three 0-10 dials alongside its own clock; three new Faction card fields, `fear`/`need`/`secret`); Discovery Quality and Noncombat Resolution were redirected into one new mechanism instead of a stored field and a resolution mechanic — a "Suggestion Lens" step for *What Happens Next?*, which today is wired identically to Continue Story (a real gap this also names): a lens picker (Discovery/Approach categories) would filter the next Oracle roll toward a chosen creative angle instead of generating blind. The session-composition-ratio decline was reconfirmed unchanged.',
    '2026-07-06 Traveller/SWN content, on direct user request (reverses one specific call from docs/adr/0002-rules-constitution.md — see docs/adr/0010-traveller-swn-content.md): Traveller gains a real data/rulesets.js character ruleset — STR/DEX/END/INT/EDU/SOC collapsed to this app\'s usual small-rollable-modifier abstraction (not literal 2-12 UPP scores + a separately-derived DM, which would make 2d6+value vs 8 trivially easy), one Stamina track (0-8) standing in for Traveller\'s three-stat damage system, finally giving domain/dice.js\'s rollTraveller (2d6 vs 8, unused since Phase 6) an actual sheet to belong to. No sourcebook exists in assets/docs/ for either system, so this is honestly-labeled original content, not a transcription — doc: null, and the Settings drawer\'s Stat System reference link now shows "No sourcebook in this repo\'s library..." instead of a broken link whenever a ruleset has no doc. SWN gains a new "Stars Without Number" oracle group instead (Faction Action, World Tag — original phrasing inspired by SWN\'s faction-turn and two-tag world-generation conventions, not its actual proprietary tables), reachable as a second roll button on the Faction Pressure Track\'s card alongside the existing Hostile-flavored Faction Activity roll — an ordinary oracle addition, not a genre-pack swap. rulesConstitution.js\'s status strings for both updated accordingly.',
    '2026-07-06 Faction-turn/rumor automation, scoped deliberately small (a GM-triggered bulk action, not a background scheduler or live simulation — Article II, the GM always retains creative authority): domain/factions.js\'s advanceFactionTurns() advances every faction that already has a Pressure Track by one tick and rolls a "rumor" for each from the existing Faction Activity oracle table (factions with no track are skipped — nothing to advance for one nobody\'s tracking). A new "Advance Faction Turns" button in the Journal drawer rolls a turn for every tracked faction at once and journals the results together (formatFactionTurnRumors()) — the concrete, small shape "faction-turn/rumor automation" takes here rather than the full Living World Engine the original design corpus describes.',
    '2026-07-06 Faction Pressure Track, Mission generator, and the Faction Rumor -> Mission seed link (the trio ADR 0004\'s ruleset review scoped for Phase 10): domain/factions.js models a faction\'s pressure clock as a Thread tagged kind: \'faction-pressure\' plus a factionId reference — the same "reuse Threads" pattern Contracts already established, so every existing Thread control works on one unchanged. Opt-in per faction (a "+ Pressure Track" button in the Faction card, not auto-created); a new free-text Agenda field and a "Faction Activity" oracle table (Corporate Powers group) round it out. domain/missions.js\'s generateMission() returns payout/deadline/complication/penalty scaled by context.what.threat (higher ambient danger = higher stakes, tighter deadline, automatically) and rolls its complication from the existing Story Complication table; a new "Generate Mission" button in the Journal drawer rolls one straight into a note. copilot.js\'s advise() now surfaces a faction whose pressure track is >=75% full as a mission seed ("a mission tied to them would land naturally now"), ranked just below a hot ordinary thread. Building this surfaced and fixed a real bug: the hot-thread check read campaign.threads unfiltered, so a near-full Contract or Faction Pressure Track (both stored there too) got flagged with the wrong generic thread phrasing instead of their own subsystem\'s message — now excludes anything carrying a kind tag.',
    '2026-07-06 Dice roll window follow-up: repositioned to the bottom-right corner (like a toast, but persistent until dismissed) instead of a centered, backdrop-dimmed modal — the rest of the app stays reachable while a roll result is up, since there\'s no more full-screen backdrop blocking clicks. New "add to Journal" button (an open-book SVG icon, not the 📖 emoji — unreliable glyph coverage here too, same fix as the die-face icons) pastes the same plain-text breakdown the copy button produces, prefixed with the roll\'s label, as a Journal note — distinct from the terse one-line entry every roll already logs automatically.',
    '2026-07-06 Anchor displacement, Cast joins the drawer system, and a graphical dice roll window: (1) Anchoring a second drawer no longer discards whichever one was already anchored — it\'s restored to the tab group first (anchorDrawerTab), so nothing gets silently closed just because something else took the anchor slot. (2) Cast is now a real drawer (its own DRAWERS entry, renderDrawer case, tab strip anchor/close icons) instead of a bespoke separate popout with its own CSS/skeleton/responsive rules — toggleCastDrawer keeps its one special behavior (opens into the anchor slot by default, since a draggable entity list is most useful beside whichever drawer IS active) but once open it behaves exactly like any other drawer, including "move back into the tab group." Its "Generate…" dropdown moved from a hardcoded popout header into a generic .drawer-head-actions/data-drawer-head-extra slot both the main drawer and the anchor panel now support. (3) Statblock rolls open a real dice roll window instead of a plain toast: the action die (or flat/Traveller die) and the field\'s value added up on one row (an SVG pip-die icon, not a Unicode ⚀-⚅ glyph — unreliable font/platform glyph coverage), what it\'s measured against on another (a diamond icon for Starforged\'s 2d10 challenge, a target icon for a flat/Traveller target number), and a big color-coded outcome banner (green/amber/red for strong hit/weak hit/miss, green/red for success/fail). A ⧉ button copies the result as plain text (domain/dice.js\'s new formatRollCopyText/formatFlatRollCopyText/formatTravellerRollCopyText) in the exact tab-indented "Action: .../Challenge: .../OUTCOME" shape requested; still logs to the Journal exactly as before.',
    '2026-07-05 Anchored drawers, genre-aware Bestiary/LifeForm terminology, and Contract journaling: (1) Any drawer tab can now be pulled out of the tab stack and pinned to its own side panel immediately left of the main drawer (the tab strip\'s new ⇤ icon; the anchor panel\'s own ▶ moves it back) — rolling from the Oracle drawer itself now auto-anchors Journal to Oracle\'s left, so the entry the roll just logged is visible without switching tabs, without stealing the anchor slot if something else already occupies it. (2) "Bestiary" (a fantasy-genre term) now reads "LifeForm" for the Hostile/Cyberpunk genre packs, switching back to "Bestiary" only for the Fantasy pack (data/genrePacks.js\'s new bestiaryTerm()) — the Settings template editor, the entity inspector\'s statblock group header, the "+ Add a statblock" chip, and the Party roster\'s per-group caption all read it live off settings.genrePack; the underlying mechanism (data/statblockTemplates.js\'s NPC field manifests) is unchanged, this only ever swaps the label. (3) Creating a contract (domain/trade.js\'s createContract, so both the "+ Contract" form and "Generate" get it for free) now logs a Journal entry with its type/patron/route/payout resolved to entity names, the same way generateNpc()/rollOracle() already record what they created.',
    '2026-07-05 Phase 10 begins — Merchant Rules Lens (ADR 0003/0004): a new Trade drawer (between Colony and Docs) adds a per-Location commodity market (data/commodities.js + domain/trade.js\'s priceAt() — supply/demand dials drive price, buying/selling nudges the local dial so two Locations\' prices never agree), the party\'s shared cargo manifest, and a Contract board. A contract is a Thread with a few extra reference fields (kind: \'contract\', type, patronId/originId/destinationId, payout) rather than a new state machine, so its clock/lifecycle/priority controls are the exact same ones every other Thread already has. "Generate" rolls a new Contract Type oracle table (Trade & Cargo group, ADR 0004\'s 15-type taxonomy) and prices the payout from the real gap between two Locations\' markets when a route is picked, falling back to a flat default otherwise; "+ Contract" opens an inline name/type/patron/route/payout form, not a window.prompt() popup. Cargo capacity rides the existing Vehicle Bestiary template as one more field. Everything ADR 0004 explicitly deferred (ships/crew depth, faction politics, the rest of the 19-generator list, GM-less/VTT modes) stays deferred.',
    '2026-07-05 Stress/Tension — the reopened Phase 6 candidate: a fifth context.what narrative dial (drawn from Hostile\'s horror-design essay, Setting pp.211-219 — uncertainty/isolation/timing as the three horror levers), same shape as Resources/Reputation (0-10, neutral-midpoint-5 default so no old save suddenly reads as already-cracking). New Raise Stress/Ease Stress Shift actions and a third slider on the WHAT view (field-row-3col alongside Resources/Reputation). The Co-Pilot now reacts at both ends: high Stress (>=7) surfaces as an observation/consequence ranked just below Threat ("Stress is high — a scene without combat should follow, or someone breaks" / "Someone cracks under the pressure..."), with a suggested Horror Escalation -> Escalation Beat oracle roll and an Ease Stress quick-action; very low Stress (<=2) offers a calm-holds opportunity, mirroring Resources/Reputation\'s abundance case.',
    '2026-07-05 Three follow-up fixes to the same day\'s UI polish pass: (1) Party roster cards are now full drawer width (was a wrapping row of ~13rem-cap cards) — a full ruleset\'s stat row usually needs no horizontal scrollbar anymore. (2) Party Tracker rows no longer name their own kind ("Meter"/"Counter") — the format (boxes vs. a +/- number) already says which one it is; a Starforged counter\'s difficulty rank still shows (nothing else reveals it), just without the redundant kind word glued in front. (3) The graph layout\'s centering pull was raised from 0.012 to 10 — at the wider ideal-edge-length from earlier the same day, that pull was so weak relative to repulsion that nodes drifted to the pad boundary and stayed there regardless of graph size ("not evenly spaced... pushed to the border"); the new value was tuned empirically (a standalone sweep across 2-50 node graphs) to keep the overwhelming majority of nodes off the border while still spreading them across most of the canvas.',
    '2026-07-05 UI polish pass across Cast/Entity Detail/Graph/Party: (1) Cast\'s row of per-type "+ Add" chips is now one small "Generate…" dropdown docked next to the panel\'s own close ✕ (folding in the old separate "🎲 Generate NPC" oracle-roll button as one of its options), which let the search box move up to sit directly under the Cast header instead of below a whole button row. (2) The Entity Detail tag editor\'s "add tag" input now shares a row with the TAGS caption (right-aligned) instead of stacking below it. (3) The relationship graph\'s force layout uses a larger ideal-edge-length constant (was tuned tight enough that a busy graph\'s lines crossed each other illegibly) — while retuning it, found and fixed a real pre-existing bug: nodes were only clamped to the layout box once, at the very end, so a busy graph\'s outer nodes could overshoot by different amounts each pass and then collapse onto the exact same boundary corner when finally clamped, silently stacking distinct entities on top of each other; clamping every iteration instead means nodes bounce off the wall and settle at genuinely distinct positions. (4) Party roster cards now show one row per statblock GROUP (with a small ruleset/template caption above each), not every group\'s fields flattened together — a character carrying two rulesets\' sheets now reads as two distinguishable rows instead of one undifferentiated pile of badges. (5) Party Trackers: "+ Tracker" opens a small inline name/type form (a text field, not a window.prompt() popup); a tracker\'s kind is fixed forever once created (no more per-tracker kind <select>); a Meter asks its box count at creation ("usually 5 or 10 in Starforged") and renders as click-to-set progress boxes instead of a "value/max" ratio; a Counter offers a Starforged progress-track difficulty rank (Troublesome..Epic) when the campaign\'s stat ruleset is Starforged, stepping by that rank\'s tick count (out of a 40-tick track) instead of a plain +1.',
    '2026-07-05 Four oracle-content additions from the design-roadmap reconciliation\'s unblocked-follow-ups list (data only, no new domain code): "Salvage Investigation" (Derelicts group gains What Happened/What Remains/Still Changing) turns a derelict from a one-note flavor roll into a small mystery chain — what wrecked it, what\'s left behind, what\'s still active and dangerous about it right now. "Site Survey" (Exploration group gains What\'s Normal/What\'s Strange/What\'s Dangerous/What\'s Valuable/What\'s Beautiful) is deliberately discovery-first — only one of its five tables is about danger, the rest are about what a survey actually finds. "Cargo Interest" (Trade & Cargo) answers who unexpectedly wants a given shipment and why. "Anomaly Investigation" (Mysteries & Coverups gains Observation/Hypothesis/Contradiction/Discovery) gives an oracle-driven shape to investigating something strange, the same way Coverup Move already gave one to investigating a lie. All four are ordinary tables rolled in the Oracle drawer like the app\'s other 100+ tables — no new UI, no new reducer, just data alongside each group\'s existing tables.',
    '2026-07-05 Fixed a real all-caps rendering bug + two smaller cleanups: WHO/WHERE/WHAT/WHY/HOW\'s mention-editor fields inherited text-transform: uppercase from their <label class="field-label"> wrapper (that rule is meant for the label\'s own small caption text, e.g. "SITUATION") — with no override, it shouted the field\'s actual content too, entity/doc mention text included, while Journal (wrapped in .drawer-note, no such rule) and Guide (no wrapper) were unaffected, matching exactly what was reported ("caps in most textfields, but Guide is fine"). Fixed with one explicit text-transform: none on .mention-editor. Also: a relationship\'s strength/weight control (and the Bond-tracker display it can stand in for) no longer renders at all unless BOTH sides are an NPC or a Faction — a Location, some Lore, or an Asset doesn\'t have an evolving "how strong is this" dial, so showing an editable number there meant nothing. And: the Guide editor autosaves on blur now (no Save button — nothing else in the app uses one; every other field already commits on blur/change).',
    '2026-07-05 Edge nav reorder + drag-drop/doc-link fixes: edge nav top-down order is now Guide, Journal, Oracle, Party, Cast, Colony, Docs, Graph, Co-Pilot, Settings (Cast/Co-Pilot are special-cased non-drawer buttons, not part of DRAWERS, so this needed one combined EDGE_ORDER list instead of DRAWERS.map() + always-appended extras). Dragging an entity from Cast onto Entity Detail (anywhere in the editor, not just the Relationships section) now adds it as a relationship, the same addRelationship() a Cast-row-to-Cast-row drop already used — the whole .entity-inspector is a drop target now, not just other Cast rows. Root-caused why a Guide/Journal doc mention link sometimes refused to open the PDF viewer ("Text notes open inline below — not a PDF file"): linkDocumentMentions never checked the Reference Library before deciding a mentioned title didn\'t exist yet, so it could create a phantom same-titled TEXT NOTE that permanently shadowed the real Reference Library PDF for every future mention of that title (findDocumentTabByTitle checked the uploaded library first, unconditionally). Fixed both ends: linkDocumentMentions now skips Reference Library matches too, and findDocumentTabByTitle now prefers whichever match is actually openable over a same-titled non-PDF note, which also self-heals any campaign where the phantom note already exists. Also: uploaded file titles are no longer the raw filename verbatim (extension included) — titleCase.js (new, shared with the Reference Library\'s own build-time title generation) strips the extension/hyphens and proper-cases ALL-CAPS segments, so an upload named "HOSTILE-SHORTS-999-Test.pdf" shows as "Hostile Shorts 999 Test" instead of shouting inline wherever it\'s mentioned.',
    '2026-07-05 Design roadmap reconciliation: evaluated `requirements/design-principles/gameplay-mechanics.md` (a campaign-structure/mechanics research transcript) against this repo (`docs/adr/0008-situation-engine.md`). Documentation only, no code: most of what it proposed — a "GM Prompt Hierarchy," an "Oracle Prompt Chain" technique, "Campaign Momentum" — turned out to already be this repo\'s WHAT card + Shift Story reducers, generateNpc\'s multi-table roll, and Session Recap + Co-Pilot, respectively, arrived at independently; now named and cross-referenced instead of re-treated as gaps. Four small oracle-content additions (Salvage Investigation, Site Survey, Cargo Interest, Anomaly Investigation) were scoped as unblocked, low-effort follow-ups (see `DESIGN-NEW-FUNCTIONALITY.md`\'s new unphased content section); an Expedition four-dial tracker, structured Diplomacy fields, a Discovery-classification field, a Noncombat taxonomy, and a mechanized session-composition budget were all explicitly declined, with reasons, in the ADR.',
    '2026-07-05 Cast/Entity Detail split: Cast is no longer a drawer tab — it\'s a Co-Pilot-style independent panel (toggled from its own edge button, same list — search, type filter, add-entity buttons, draggable/clickable rows — the drawer always rendered) that stays open alongside whichever drawer IS active, so an entity can be dragged into Journal or Guide while the Cast list stays visible instead of competing with them for the one active-drawer slot (this supersedes the separate 📌 entity-popout added the day before — same need, now solved by promoting Cast itself rather than a second parallel panel). The name/tags/overview/statblocks/relationships form Cast used to show inline moved to its own "Entity Detail" tab — it has no edge nav button at all, and only ever opens by clicking an entity somewhere (a Cast row, a mention link, a relationship chip, a graph node, a WHO/WHERE chip, a search result, ...), never picked from the tab list directly. Both panels get the same phone (bottom sheet) / tablet (edge slide-in) responsive treatment Co-Pilot already had, so Cast staying reachable on a phone didn\'t regress now that it has no drawer-tab fallback.',
    '2026-07-05 Relationship type validity + Starforged Bond tracker: Rival Of/Allied With/Bond are social relationship types that only make sense between people and factions (an Asset or Location can\'t have a rivalry) — extended the existing "flag, don\'t delete" pattern (already used for Member Of/Owns/Controls/Located At\'s directional target-type checks) to these three as well, checking BOTH sides now (entities.js\'s new RELATIONSHIP_TYPE_MUTUAL), not just the target. A Bond\'s progress no longer lives on the relationship object\'s generic 0-10 strength field at all — the moment a relationship becomes bond-typed (between an NPC/Faction pair), if the source entity has a Starforged character sheet, a real "Bond: <Name>" progress track is auto-created there (entities.js\'s ensureBondTrack), matching how the rulebook actually presents Bonds (pp.163-166/233) instead of inventing a second progress-track shape. The relationship chip shows that track\'s current value read-only (not a second editable copy of the same number) with a "view in Character Sheet" jump button that expands the group if collapsed and scrolls to it. Also added: a "✕ close all" button in the drawer tab strip\'s corner (separate from a single tab\'s own ✕, which only ever closed that one tab), and Reference Library titles generated from ALL-CAPS filenames (e.g. "HOSTILE SHORTS 001GhostShip") are now proper-cased at build time ("Hostile Shorts 001GhostShip") since those titles are exactly what a @[Title] mention shows as link text — a short allowlist (5PFH, GM, NPC, PDF, SWN) keeps real acronyms from being mangled.',
    '2026-07-05 Mention click behavior + a real auto-create bug: reverted yesterday\'s Ctrl/Cmd+Click requirement for opening a mention — a single click now opens the entity (and focuses+selects its name field in the Cast inspector) or the document (PDF viewer) directly, matching Notion/Google Docs\' convention rather than Word\'s; editing a mention\'s label is done by arrow-keying the cursor into it like any other inline text, not by clicking it (clicking is unambiguously "go there" now). Root-caused a real reported bug along the way: asking a document mention for a page (@[Title#12], from the "which page?" prompt) was silently creating a new NPC entity named literally "Title#12" instead of linking the document — entities.js\'s parseMentions/linkMentions had never stripped a page anchor (only a @[Label|...] prefix), so a page-anchored mention\'s "name" was the whole "Title#12" string, which never matches an existing entity and so always got auto-created as one. Fixed the stripping, and added a second, deeper guard: linkMentions now takes a `skip` set of names already known to resolve to a real document (documents.js\'s new resolvedDocumentMentionNames) — without it, a mention of an existing document that ISN\'T also an uploaded library entry (e.g. anything in the Reference Library) would still have gotten auto-created as a phantom entity, page anchor or not, since linkMentions has no way to know the document library exists at all.',
    '2026-07-05 @mentions are now inline hyperlinks in the text itself, not badges below it: Journal, Guide, and WHO/WHERE/WHAT/WHY/HOW are now contenteditable (ui/mentionEditor.js — buildMentionEditorHTML/serializeMentionEditor), not <textarea>, so a mention renders as real inline text living exactly where it was typed, matching how a hyperlink sits inline in a web page or an MS Word document. Editing its display label is just editing text — click into the mention and type, the same convention Word itself uses for an editable hyperlink; the underlying target is a fixed data attribute on the span, never touched by editing the visible label (confirmed: precisely editing a label leaves data-open-entity pointing at the same entity). Since editing-in-place needed a real distinction between "editing the label" and "following the link," navigating is now Ctrl/Cmd+Click — a plain click falls through to the browser\'s normal caret placement instead (this is also gated to only inline .mention-link spans; every other data-open-entity/data-doc-open use — WHO/WHERE chips, Party cards, relationship chips, the graph — still opens on a plain click as before). Drag-and-drop and the @-suggestion popup now insert a real mention element directly (mentionEditor.js\'s insertMentionNode via the Selection/Range API) instead of raw @[...] text waiting for a future re-render to become a link. This fully supersedes the previous day\'s "chip below the textbox with a ✎ button" mechanism — removed the now-dead relabelJournalMention/relabelGuideMention/relabelContextMention/relabelMention functions and their UI wiring along with it, rather than leaving two mention-editing paths half-working side by side.',
    '2026-07-04 @-mention autocomplete, entity popout, whole-row drag, clickable relationships: typing "@" plus a few characters of a name in Journal, the Guide, or any WHO/WHERE/WHAT/WHY/HOW field now pops up a filtered list of matching entities/documents (Up/Down/Enter/Escape or click) that inserts a finished @Name/@[Name] mention in place — for a document, asking which page first, same as the drag-and-drop path. Every one of those fields also now renders its @mentions as clickable badges (not just Journal/Guide, which already got this in an earlier pass this same day) — a real reported case, @[AR-5 "Prospector"], is now clickable end-to-end confirmed with an actual quote-containing entity name. New: an Entity popout (📌 Entities, next to the Co-Pilot toggle) — a draggable-only Cast quick-list docked beside whichever drawer is open, so an entity can be dragged into Journal or Guide while the Cast list stays visible instead of replacing it (only one drawer body is ever in the DOM at a time, so this was otherwise impossible); desktop-only, since phone/tablet already have the autocomplete and touch drag-and-drop for the same need. Also: the Guide editor was never actually wired into the drag-and-drop drop-target list at all (despite its own placeholder text describing @mentions) — entities and documents can now be dropped there same as Journal. Cast list rows are draggable from anywhere on the row again, not just the small ⠿ handle (reverted from an earlier click-vs-drag-conflict fix, accepting the known tradeoff — real mouse jitter can occasionally start a drag instead of a click — in exchange for "grab it anywhere" being more discoverable). And: an entity\'s relationship chips now have a clickable name that jumps to that entity, instead of being plain text next to the type/label/strength controls.',
    '2026-07-04 Graph zoom/pan + two more fixes: the relationship graph (SVG, fixed 600x520 layout space) had no way to zoom in — a campaign with a lot of entities/links just got visually cramped with no recourse. Added scroll-wheel zoom (centered on the cursor), drag-to-pan, and ＋/－/⟲ toolbar buttons, all manipulating the rendered SVG\'s viewBox directly rather than a full re-render (buildGraph/computeLayout, a force-directed layout, has no reason to re-run just because the view into it moved) — clicking a node still opens its Cast inspector as before, unaffected by the new pan handler. Also: the Documents drawer\'s rename ✎ button only opened the inline input — clicking it again while already editing (instead of blurring/tabbing away) silently did nothing, which read as "doesn\'t save"; it now saves-and-closes on that second click (and shows 💾 instead of ✎ while open, as a hint). And: dragging a Reference Library entry into a note or context field inserted a raw `file:///.../index.html#` string instead of an @mention — Reference Library rows were never wired into the custom drag-and-drop system (missing draggable/data-drag-document), so the browser fell back to its native default drag behavior for the link. Fixed by giving them the same drag wiring as uploaded documents (keyed by the existing "ref:<path>" tab-key format, resolved via resolveDocumentTab) — dropping one now inserts a real, clickable @[Title] mention like an uploaded document always did.',
    '2026-07-04 Clickable/editable @mentions + Cast drawer cleanup: @mentions in Journal entries and the Guide now render as one clickable badge each — data-open-entity for an entity match (jumps to its Cast inspector), data-doc-open for a document match (opens the PDF viewer, to the mentioned page), plain/non-clickable if neither resolves — instead of entity mentions rendering only their stat badges (no click-to-open at all) while the Guide\'s own mentions were static, non-clickable spans. New syntax `@[Label|Target]` (documents.js\'s splitLabel/relabelMention, entities.js\'s parseMentionRefs) lets a mention\'s displayed text diverge from what it resolves to — "the topic of the page" for a document anchor, or a narrative nickname for an entity — auto-/link-create still keys off the real target, never the label. Every badge gets a small ✎ that swaps it for an inline rename input (relabelJournalMention/relabelGuideMention persist the rewritten @[...] text) instead of a window.prompt() popup. Also: the Cast drawer\'s entity-list collapse toggle used to be a second "Cast — N entities ▾" row directly under the drawer\'s own "Cast" title — redundant, two labels for one thing. The drawer title itself is now the toggle (collapsed by default every time the tab is (re)opened, and now hides the add-entity buttons too, not just the search/filter/list below them), and the Cast type-filter chips (All/NPC/Location/...) are alphabetized by label instead of ENTITY_TYPES\' declaration order.',
    '2026-07-04 Tag UX unification + Documents cleanup: the entity tag editor (Cast drawer) used an older pattern — a `<select>` dropdown plus a separate "+ New…" window.prompt() button — while the Documents drawer\'s tag editor (from the previous fix pass) used a single input+datalist that just commits on its own. The doc version is now the one tag-entry design everywhere: entity tags dropped the select/prompt pair for the same auto-committing input (data-entity-tag-input), sharing its datalist-suggestion-or-type-new-then-blur/Enter behavior and even its CSS class. Documents drawer: removed the "Add note" button and its window.prompt() flow entirely (uploading a file is still there; existing note-kind documents from before this change still display and save normally, just can\'t be created fresh anymore) — the "No documents match…" placeholder that referenced the now-gone note feature is gone too (an empty list is just empty). The tag-filter chip row is now collapsed by default behind a "▸ Tags (N)" toggle instead of always showing every tag in the campaign at once.',
    '2026-07-04 Documents/mentions fix pass: root-caused "the @ link to docs is not working" and "entities showing up as documents" to the same bug — bare @Name and bracketed @[Name] mentions share identical syntax (brackets only exist so a multi-word name survives the parser), so linkDocumentMentions (documents.js) couldn\'t tell an entity mention from a document one and auto-created a same-named phantom "document" (empty note body) for EVERY entity mentioned in a Journal note or context field; documentBadges then rendered a dead, non-clickable 📄 badge for that same name right next to the entity\'s real attribute badge, which is what read as a broken link. Fixed at both ends: linkDocumentMentions now skips names that already resolve to an entity, and documentBadges skips names that resolve to an entity (entities get exactly one badge — their own — not two). Also, while in this area: Reference Library entries now respect the Documents drawer\'s search box and tag filters (previously only the uploaded/note library did); gained a delete (✕) icon — since they\'re build artifacts from assets/docs/, this hides the entry via a persisted per-campaign override rather than touching the file, with the same confirm-dialog pattern as deleting an uploaded document; and switched their internal tab-key scheme from a positional array index to the manifest\'s stable file path (a latent bug the new search/hide filtering would otherwise have exposed — a filtered list\'s Nth item is not the same as the manifest\'s Nth item). The rename (✎) button on both uploaded docs and Reference Library entries now opens an inline textbox in place of the title instead of a window.prompt() popup. Tag entry (both libraries) no longer needs a separate "+" click: picking a tag from the datalist or typing a new one and tabbing/Enter-ing away both commit immediately (mirrors how the entity tag dropdown already worked).',
    '2026-07-04 Cast/statblock UX pass: investigated a "drag-and-drop is not working" report and confirmed the actual behavior (dragging from a Cast row\'s body correctly does nothing — only the ⠿ grip drags, a deliberate earlier fix for a click-vs-drag conflict) is by design, not a regression; made the grip visually more discoverable (bigger hit target, hover background/border) since it\'s easy to miss coming from the old whole-row-draggable behavior. Each statblock group (Bestiary/Character Sheet/Vehicle) in the entity inspector is now independently collapsible via a ▾/▸ toggle in its header (ui/shell.js\'s collapsedStatblockGroups, keyed per entity+group so collapsing one doesn\'t affect others) — the Cast list itself already had this from an earlier fix; this extends it to the statblock sections within an entity\'s inspector. Character-sheet stat rows (Edge/Heart/Iron/Shadow/Wits, Reaction/Speed/Combat/Savvy/Tough) are narrower and no longer wrap to a second line — a full 5-stat ruleset now reads as one row in the drawer, with horizontal scroll as the fallback if a custom ruleset ever has more. Follow-up: the Party tab\'s member-card stat badges (.attr-badge — a separate, older read-only-summary style shared with Journal entity-mention badges, not the character-sheet rows above) were still full-size and the card itself had no width cap, so 5+ badges just kept the card growing wider instead of wrapping; narrowed .attr-badge to match and capped .party-member-card at 13rem so badges wrap into tidy rows instead.',
    'Phase 9 complete — genre packs: data/genrePacks.js registers three selectable oracle table sets (Hostile sci-fi, the pre-existing default; Cyberpunk/Shadowrun; Fantasy/D&D-style — the two new ones are original content in this project\'s own voice), switchable from a new Settings → "Genre Pack" dropdown (settings.genrePack, defaults to \'hostile\' so every existing campaign is unaffected). domain/oracles.js\'s tablesWithOverrides() now takes a genrePackId and every caller threads campaign.settings.genrePack through — Continue Story, oracle rolls, Generate NPC, Universal Search, and the Oracle drawer\'s tree/entry editor all respect the active pack. The two new packs deliberately reuse the exact category names (Characters, Location Themes, Plot Engine, Miscellaneous, Trade & Cargo) that the Co-Pilot\'s suggested-oracle logic and Generate NPC\'s NPC chain reference by hardcoded path, so those features work unchanged no matter which pack is active — this is a data swap, not a new mechanism. Verified in a browser: switching packs changes Generate NPC\'s name pool, the Oracle drawer\'s content, scene generation, and search results, with zero effect on anything else.',
    '2026-07-04 reliability + UX pass, run after a full regression check confirmed Phase 9\'s Activity picker and everything before it: (1) Settings shows campaign storage size + a "Restore last backup" button (store.js\'s storageInfo()/restoreBackup() — the one-slot backup from ADR 0005 had no restore UI until now). (2) The Pages deploy workflow gained a post-deploy smoke check that fetches the live site and verifies the bundle actually resolves, plus (added the same day) a check that a sample LFS-tracked PDF resolves to real content, not a pointer file. (3) The Reference Library\'s PDFs (~445MB) moved to Git LFS, including a history rewrite (backed by a mirror clone, confirmed via a fresh clone afterward) — caught and fixed a real regression this surfaced (actions/checkout needs lfs:true or LFS files deploy as pointer text). (4) Drawers are now tabbed: multiple can stay pinned open at once (openDrawers/activeDrawer replacing the old single openDrawer), with a tab strip that only appears once 2+ are open. (5) Three real responsive tiers instead of one: tablet (768-1023px) now gets a Co-Pilot side panel that slides in from the edge like a drawer, distinct from phone\'s (<768px) bottom sheet. (6) Two keyboard shortcuts: Escape (close whatever\'s topmost) and Ctrl/Cmd+K (open Universal Search). (7) Touch drag-and-drop: a gesture recognizer for entity linking and @mention-by-drag now works on real touch devices (HTML5 DnD never fires for touch at all), sharing the same completeDrop() logic the mouse path uses — see docs/mobile-drag-drop-test-cases.md for the manual device checklist. (8) A PWA installability audit (Chrome DevTools Protocol, not just eyeballing the manifest) came back clean — zero installability errors, service worker/offline mode both verified by actually going offline and reloading — except the app icon still read "SA" (leftover Saga Atlas branding); regenerated as "GM" in the exact same style.',
    'Phase 9 (Activity-driven gameplay) begins — the HOW workspace question gains an Activity picker (Explore/Investigate/Negotiate/Travel/Trade/Combat/Faction dealings/Downtime/Horror/World-building, new domain/activities.js) that turns data/rulesConstitution.js\'s Rules Constitution from a read-only Settings reference into an actual recommender: picking an Activity looks up its registered gameplay area and shows the Rules Lens provider(s) responsible for it (e.g. Combat -> Five Parsecs From Home), with a "Use as default" button that sets settings.statRuleset — suggestion only, never automatic, extending the existing per-entity ruleset selector rather than replacing it. Genre packs (this phase\'s other item) remain open.',
    'Root cause found and fixed (the previous build\'s toast surfaced the symptom; this fixes the real bug): store.js\'s persist() wrote a full duplicate of the previous save to a backup key BEFORE writing the real one — momentarily needing quota for two whole copies of the campaign at once. Once a campaign (typically one with large embedded document uploads) crossed roughly half of localStorage\'s quota, that backup write started failing, and because it was treated as fatal, it silently blocked EVERY subsequent save — including something as simple as clicking to select a Cast entity — even though the real save alone would still have fit. Confirmed via a live error report ("Failed to execute \'setItem\' on \'Storage\': Setting the value of \'sagaatlas.campaign.backup\' exceeded the quota") and reproduced deterministically (forced only the backup key\'s write to throw; confirmed the real save failed too, then confirmed it succeeds under the fix, including surviving a reload). The backup write is now best-effort — if it can\'t fit, it\'s skipped (logged, not thrown) and the actual campaign save proceeds; the backup has no restore UI wired to it yet, so a skipped backup costs nothing today, but a blocked real save cost everything.',
    'Fixed: any interaction that saves (store.update() — includes something as simple as clicking to select a Cast entity) writes the whole campaign document to localStorage; if that write fails (most commonly localStorage quota exceeded — real-world cause: large uploaded PDFs stored as embedded data, see store.js\'s persist()), the change was correctly rolled back but this threw with no visible feedback, so the click just looked like it did nothing. Root-caused via a deterministic repro (forced localStorage.setItem to throw, confirmed clicking a Cast row silently failed to select while filter-only interactions — pure in-memory state, no save involved — kept working, matching a real report: "filter works, select doesn\'t"). Fixed at the one choke point every interaction already passes through (ui/shell.js\'s single delegated click/change/input/dblclick listeners, rule 4): a `guarded()` wrapper now catches any handler failure and shows a toast ("Couldn\'t save — ... Storage may be full; try exporting your campaign as a backup") instead of swallowing it silently. If you\'re seeing this: export your campaign (Settings → Export Campaign JSON) as a backup, then free up space by removing large uploaded documents (or moving big rulebooks into assets/docs/ + rebuild instead, which has no storage-quota limit).',
    'Phase 8 (Unified Discovery) complete — four items: (1) Universal Search: a new 🔍 Search button in the header opens an overlay searching entities, journal, oracle tables (names and individual entries), documents (uploaded/text + Reference Library), Party trackers, and Colony fields/crew in one query (domain/search.js\'s universalSearch(), pure and DOM-free — it returns declarative targets, ui/searchPanel.js and shell.js do the navigating); clicking a result jumps straight to it (opens the entity, the document tab, or the Oracle drawer pre-filtered to the matched table). (2) Oracle table editor: each table in the Oracle drawer gets an ✎ toggle to add/edit/remove its entries and a "↺ Reset to default" once changed, built on the existing oracles.overrides mechanism (no second data path) — the drawer\'s tree also now reads through tablesWithOverrides so an edited table displays correctly, not just rolls correctly. Two new content additions shipped alongside it: a "Scenario Framing" oracle group (Dilemma/Objective/Framing NPCs/Map Feature) and an "Environmental Hazards" group (25-entry Environmental Event table + Survey Problem table), both original content. (3) Cast drawer gained a name/tag search box and entity-type filter chips above the list. (4) NPC generation oracle chain: the existing Characters oracle group (Role/Goal/Revealed Aspect/Disposition) gained a Name table to complete the chain, and a new 🎲 Generate NPC button (domain/session.js\'s generateNpc()) rolls all five into a new NPC in one click — plus a 5PFH-style Patron Benefit/Hazard/Danger Pay job-offer table set under Missions.',
    'Fixed: a Cast-list row was both the click target (select this entity) AND the drag source (draggable="true", to create a relationship) — for a real mouse, a few pixels of jitter between mousedown and mouseup is enough for the browser to start a native drag instead of firing a click, which suppressed selection entirely and made the whole Cast list feel unresponsive (reported: "clicking an entity does not make it active, dragging does not work either"). Dragging is now confined to a small ⠿ grip inside each row; the row itself is click-only (drop targets never needed draggable in the first place). The Relationships section\'s "Link" button is now icon-labeled (🔗 Link), and each relationship\'s remove control is titled "Remove link" for clarity. The Cast drawer\'s entity list can now be collapsed to just a header (▸ Cast — N entities · editing X) via a toggle, leaving the full inspector for the active entity with more room.',
    'Phase 7 (Context Graph depth) complete — three more items: (1) Typed/weighted relationships: a relationship now carries a semantic type (Linked/Member Of/Owns/Controls/Located At/Allied With/Rival Of/Bond, domain/entities.js\'s RELATIONSHIP_TYPES) alongside its free-text label, plus a 0-10 strength weight — a Starforged Bond is just a `bond`-typed relationship whose strength a GM raises over time, not a second mechanism. The requested type applies only to the side that requested it (per-side, like the existing label editor); every pre-existing relationship normalizes to linked/0 the moment any setter touches it. (2) "Flag, don\'t delete" invalid relationships (pack 9): a directional type (Member Of/Owns/Controls/Located At) implies a target entity type; when the target\'s own type is edited out from under it, the relationship chip gets a ⚠ (tooltip explains why) and the Co-Pilot gains a "Relationships to review" card — nothing is auto-corrected or removed. (3) Faction card template: faction entities gain hq/leadership/scenarioSeed fields (Hostile\'s "Agencies & Corporations" pattern, Setting pp.79-111), shown as a "Faction card" section in the inspector.',
    '`@` pointers into documents gain page anchors: `@[Doc Title#12]` or `@[Doc Title p.12]` names a page alongside the title (domain/documents.js\'s parseDocumentMentionRefs). A document badge that resolves to an openable PDF — an uploaded/library file or a Reference Library entry, whichever matches the title (findDocumentTabByTitle) — now renders as a clickable button (Journal entries, Guide) that opens the existing in-app viewer and jumps straight to that page via a `#page=N` fragment (openDocumentTab/resolveDocumentTab track a per-tab requested page); re-focusing an already-open tab without a page anchor leaves it wherever it already is. A text-note document mention still renders as a plain, non-clickable badge, same as before. Closes out the last piece of the old "@ pointers... like the ChatGPT version did" ask.',
    'Phase 7 (Context Graph depth) begins — tag fields as dropdowns: an entity\'s tags now render as removable chips plus a dropdown of tags already used by other entities of the same type (domain/entities.js\'s listTagVocabulary, computed live off existing entities — no separate stored vocabulary to drift out of sync). Selecting a listed tag adds it immediately; "+ New…" still takes a one-time freeform name via prompt, same pattern as "+ Field"/"+ Track" elsewhere. Replaces the old plain comma-separated text input.',
    'Fixed: a statblock value (or any text/tag field) typed but never blurred — then the browser was refreshed, closed, or the tab switched away — was silently lost, since every field only commits on the \'change\' event (fires on blur). Root-caused via a direct Playwright repro (typed a value into an attribute field, reloaded without tabbing away first, confirmed the edit reverted to its old value) after ruling out data-loss in the normal add-group/edit-value/refresh flow across file:// and http://, and across an actual rebuild. Fixed with one small addition in ui/shell.js\'s mountShell(): a \'beforeunload\'/\'visibilitychange\' listener blurs the currently-focused field, firing its pending \'change\' through the existing delegated handler — no new commit path, no per-element listeners added. This is what looked like "added statblocks are not retained" — the groups themselves were always saved instantly on click; it was in-progress field edits (a just-typed attribute value, an NPC\'s just-typed #character tag) that could be lost.',
    '5PFH dice roll toast now shows the breakdown, not just the combined total: "d6(2) + 0 = 2 vs target 6 → Fail" instead of "Fail — 2 vs target 6" — matching what the Journal entry already showed. `ui/shell.js`\'s `performFieldRoll` (\'flat\' branch) only — Starforged/Traveller toasts unchanged, not reported as an issue.',
    'Phase 6 complete — Narrative Trackers: two new campaign-level dials, Resources and Reputation (context.what, alongside threat/mystery — same "GM-set gauge the Co-Pilot reads" pattern, defaulting to a neutral 5/10 midpoint rather than 0 so an old save never suddenly reads as destitute or reviled). New Shift Story actions (Gain/Spend Resources, Raise/Lower Reputation) and two range sliders on the WHAT view. The Co-Pilot now reacts to both: critically low Resources surfaces a scarcity observation/consequence and points at the Trade & Cargo > Cargo Problem oracle table; soured Reputation surfaces as an observation/consequence about closed doors and refused help; abundant Resources or high Reputation open a new opportunity line (a favor, discount, or the room to be generous). This closes out Phase 6 (Campaign Continuity) — Session Recap, Thread lifecycle, and "What did I overlook?" all shipped in prior builds this phase.',
    'Attribute fields (Edge, Combat, Speed, ...) redesigned: the +/- steppers are gone in favor of a directly-editable, numerically-validated input (no min/max clamp — a modifier can go negative or past an old 1-5 scale). Three per-field display formats, editable in Settings\' Bestiary template editor: sign ("+3", Starforged-style, default), inches ("3\"", 5PFH Speed-style), plain ("3"). The field\'s LABEL is now the roll trigger (click "EDGE" to roll); a field with no roll method gets a plain, non-clickable label. Four dice models now available (none/Starforged d6-vs-2d10/5PFH d6-vs-target/new Traveller 2d6-vs-target, domain/dice.js\'s rollTraveller) — room is left to add more (5PFH Planetfall, Stars Without Number) as those systems get authored mechanics. 5PFH\'s Speed field ships as the concrete example: inches-formatted, not rollable.',
    'Phase 6 continued — Thread lifecycle: domain/threads.js threads now carry a 7-state narrative stage (Seeded/Active/Escalating/Dormant/Converging/Resolved/Archived) and a low/normal/high priority, GM-set via dropdowns on the Threads block (WHY question) — never auto-inferred, except that filling a clock still auto-marks it Resolved (unchanged prior behavior). "What did I overlook?" — a new Co-Pilot card (observation-only, never auto-correcting) surfaces threads gone quiet (Dormant, or untouched since creation), excluding ones already Resolved/Archived.',
    'Rules Constitution — requirements/initial design inputs/gameplay-goals.md sharpened "genre-aware, not genre-locked" into a concrete claim: every ruleset is a content provider, not the application. data/rulesConstitution.js records six named systems (Starforged, Traveller, Five Parsecs From Home, Hostile, Stars Without Number, Planetfall) mapped to gameplay areas, plus four responsibilities reserved for Saga Atlas itself (campaign memory, story continuity, rules switching, recommendations) — never delegated to a ruleset. Surfaced read-only in Settings; each provider honestly status-tagged (two of the six have zero authored data yet). Reference for Phase 9\'s future Activity → Rules Lens recommender, not an engine built ahead of its turn — see docs/adr/0002.',
    'Phase 6 (Campaign Continuity) begins — Session Recap ("Previously on...", domain/recap.js): one click in the Journal drawer composes what happened last time, open threads, the current objective, relevant entities, pressure, and a Co-Pilot recommendation from data already kept; "Save as Journal note" files it, excluding prior recaps from its own recap. Pure, read-only, and tested. Remaining Phase 6 items (Narrative Trackers beyond threat/mystery) are still open.',
    'Statblock polish — Bestiary is now explicitly an NPC subtype (like Character): statblock add-choices are scoped by entity type (Character Sheet/Bestiary only for NPCs, Vehicle Stats only for Assets; other entity types get no statblock options). Attribute/stat fields (Edge, Combat, ...) now render as a single signed number with +/- steppers instead of a 1-5 click-to-set meter — matching how Starforged/5PFH sheets actually present a stat; the 1-5 track remains for genuine depleting resources (Health, Hull). The "+ Add a statblock" chip row collapses behind a gear icon to save space once a few groups exist.',
    'Statblock redesign — an entity now holds an ARRAY of statblock groups (entity.statblocks) instead of one: a character can carry both a Starforged and a 5PFH sheet, or an NPC two Bestiary templates, simultaneously — adding one is always additive (a "+ Add" chip row), never a toggle that replaces another\'s data; each group is removable on its own via its own trash icon. Per-field UI simplified to label + value only — the rename input and the ★ (attribute)/Aa (track)/✕ (remove) buttons are gone from the entity view, since a field\'s name/kind is now fixed by its template (Settings owns that); ad-hoc "+ Field"/"+ Track" additions are named via a one-time prompt instead of an inline-editable label.',
    'Phase 5 audit — browser-verified every Phase 5 feature end to end (Playwright against the real bundle). Found and fixed one real bug: the in-app PDF viewer\'s close button was rendered but unclickable — the always-open Documents drawer sat at a higher z-index and physically overlapped it. The viewer now insets its right edge by the current drawer\'s width instead of extending underneath it.',
    'Phase 5 — design review pass against PROGRESS.md USER NOTES: three new drawers — Party (NPC #character roster + party-wide resource trackers), Colony (5PFH Planetfall turn sheet, entity-referencing crew roster, #lifeform encounter filter), Guide (freeform @mention/@[Doc]-linked reference document). Oracle drawer rebuilt as a grouped, collapsible, searchable tree (was a flat un-filterable list — the search box was silently broken). Bestiary statblock templates: per-game-system NPC field manifests (kind, roll method, sort order) editable in Settings, with a per-NPC template selector so a Bestiary can assign the right ruleset per creature; attribute badges now show a signed value ("EDGE +3"). Document Library: multi-file upload, tags + tag-filter + search, rename-the-label (not the file) via an edit button, name-as-link opening an in-app PDF viewer panel (not a new tab) beside the drawer. Entity relationships gained an editable free-text note per link. Fixed: a missing import that threw whenever the Journal rendered an entry with a @[Document] mention; the service worker cache-first strategy that could mask a rebuilt bundle indefinitely (now network-first); a GitHub Pages deploy of this repo having no dist/ bundle at all (added a build+deploy Actions workflow).',
    'Phase 4 — Document Library: assets/docs/ is auto-scanned at build time into a Reference Library (rulebooks/settings PDFs, always current with the folder); the docs drawer also supports real file uploads (stored as data URLs) alongside text notes. Character Sheets: a ruleset-driven statblock kind (Starforged or 5PFH, chosen in Settings > Stat system) builds a full rollable stat/resource-track sheet in one click, switchable between rulesets; an optional Crew Link link-out lives in Settings for full character-building wizards this app does not replicate.',
    'Phase 3D — statblock fields can be numeric tracks: a Crew-Link-style row of click-to-set boxes, with double-click on the value badge to roll (d6 + value vs 2 challenge dice, filed to the Journal). Health/Hull default to tracks; any field converts with the # / Aa toggle; "+ Track" adds a new one.',
    'Phase 3C — NPC/vehicle statblocks, drag-and-drop entity linking + drop-to-mention in Journal and context fields, this Build panel.',
    'Phase 3B — force-directed relationship graph over entity links, click-through to inspector, live edge-tab badges.',
    'Phase 3A — Entity Inspector + @mention auto-linking; WHO/WHERE cards populate from real entities.',
    'New — Threads (progress clocks) with Co-Pilot awareness.',
    'Phase 2 — interactive cockpit: Continue Story, Shift Story reducers, Oracle + Journal drawers, live Co-Pilot, timeline.',
    'Phase 1 — oracle roll engine, scene generation, context model ported as pure, tested modules.',
    'Phase 0 — single versioned campaign document, lossless migration from v0.53, three-tier cockpit shell.',
  ],
};
